Complete Version
import { useState } from 'react';

function Counter() {

    const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

    return (
        <div>
            <h2>Counter: {count}</h2>

            <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
                Increment
            </button>

            <button onClick={() => setCount(count - 1)}>
                Decrement
            </button>

            <button onClick={() => setCount(0)}>
                Reset
            </button>
        </div>
    );
}

export default Counter;
Real Example
const [name, setName] = useState("Priyadharshini");

Update:

<button onClick={() => setName("React Developer")}>
    Change Name
</button>
Interview Questions
What is useState?

useState is a React Hook used to add state to functional components.

Why useState?

To store and update data that affects the UI.

What happens when setState is called?

React re-renders the component and updates the UI with the new value.

Can useState store objects and arrays?

Yes.

const [user, setUser] = useState({
    name: "Priya",
    role: "Java Developer"
});
